If you're a whiz at the material at hand, it might be possible, and
while it still depends on the font size, margins, etc., I think 19 days
is quite a stretch for 600 pages. I certainly would not do it by myself
unless the font and margins were unusually large.

To improve translation skills, in addition to actually translating, you
can take online courses such as at www.horsefrog.com . Studying Japanese
is also important. I had passed the 1級 five years before I started
translating professionally and couldn't believe my ineptness at kanji
(not to mention everything else about the Japanese language). The JLPT
is a great metric for general comprehension and competence, but
professional translating is the difference between passing a high school
English exam and writing a scholarly criticism for a literature journal.
Okay, hyperbole, but not by much.

Also, exposure is critical. The more exposure you have, the less
ambiguous a language becomes because you gain a sense of what is likely
meant. Even native speakers can be puzzled, though, by certain
sentences, so exposure to understand what the likely interpretation of a
sentence is important.

HTH
Benjamin Barrett
