Yeah, but what is a page?

Someone asked me the other day to quote them a price for translating
&quot;a 20 to 30 minute oral presentation.&quot; I had all I could do not to
laugh. The person making the request works for a manufacturer of
electrical wiring, so next time I see him, I suppose I could ask him
how much it would cost &quot;to wire an office,&quot; just to see if he gets it.
&lt;g&gt;

Anyway, my point is that the first thing I would advise you to do is
think in concrete terms, and measure your jobs in words and
characters, not pages or slides or paragraphs or other things that
vary in size.

Think about how many Japanese characters there are, and how many
characters you can translate in an hour. Then apply your rate to that
result to see how much you would make in an hour and decide whether or
not that is commensurate with the effort it will take to get the job
done. In your case, you might feel that relatively low remuneration is
a fair trade off for the experience you will gain, which is fine, too.

Anyway, just to give you a yardstick to start measuring with, I
generally try to translate at least 400 characters an hour.

So, if a 600 page document had an average of 400 characters per page
on it, I would want to budget at least 600 hours of time to get it
done. Might not actually take that long, but I would want my client to
think that it would take that long, and I definitely do not want my
client to know how much I can translate a day. Whenever a client asks
me to specify how much I can turn out in a day, I generally give them
a figure that is about half of what I can actually do if pressed.

As for the second half of your question, sticking with subject matter
that you know well is a good way to boost productivity, but if you
still consider yourself in the &quot;apprentice&quot; stage of your career, so
to speak, forget about efficiency and consider the time it takes to
get the job done well as an investment in the future.

FWIW

