<POSTER> &quot;Warren Smith&quot; &lt;warren.sm...@comcast.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-09-12T07:47:00 </POSTDATE>
The short answer is NO.

The top translators in the world translate no more than about 2 million
words a year, or about 150,000/month (except in very unusual circumstances,
such as having extreme copyability between documents), assuming very little
time wasted in layout work.

If there are 600 pages with, lets say 500 words per page, that makes 300,000
words. You have about 2/3 month, so would have to translate at a rate of
450,000 words/month, which would take extreme effort for several of the very
top translators.

Engineering materials often have complicated equations. These tend to go
slowly, because the typing is slow. If you don't have equations, then there
are often layout issues.

For a single, relatively inexperienced translator, this is impossible
(assuming my 500 words per page assumption is even somewhat accurate, and
assuming that there is not massive internal copyability).

Yours,

Warren Smith

